{"insight":"Stop Digging Where The Well Is Full","publicTitle":"When Repetition Means Stop","plainSummary":"When the same answer keeps returning, keep what holds and move to the next honest question.","atAGlance":"We can mistake repeated insight for new discovery. If the same answer returns under many names, the work may be done. The honest task is to join what agrees, look for blind spots, and stop chasing the same point. If a different test changes the answer, the question is still alive.","keyPoints":["Meaning grows when a repeated answer becomes something we can live.","Risk begins when repetition feels like progress but only circles itself.","Test it with a different source, a different question, or a real practice."],"match":["already settled"],"tags":["discernment","practice","testing"]}
